# Backend & Agentic Framework Roadmap

This document is the **source of truth for downstream agents** extending this codebase from a single-stream “text dump” copilot into a **framework-aware, multi-model, agentic system** suitable for **high-stakes sales**: discovery calls, demos, QBRs, and technical sell-through — not only technical interviews.

---

## 0. Read this first — why we kept failing (plain English)

This section exists because **technical route tables do not explain emotional reality**: builders iterate for weeks, “fixes” land, and the demo still feels broken. That is not always incompetence; it is often **the wrong shape of system** pretending to be finished.

### 0.1 What the user actually needed vs what the code optimizes for

**What high-stakes sales / demo / discovery actually requires:**

- **Multiple parallel concerns**, all time-sensitive:
  - Listen and remember what was *committed*.
  - Track where we are in a methodology (e.g. SPIN stage, MEDDPICC gaps).
  - Surface the *next best question* without derailing rapport.
  - Handle sharp pivots (“Can you write the code?”) without forgetting the last ten minutes of biology + positioning.
  - Keep guidance **short** while analysis might be **long**.

**What this codebase primarily implements:**

- One pipe: **audio → transcript snippet → single LLM call → streaming wall of formatted text**.
- A **second** pipe (profiler) that updates “psychology” on a timer and eventually influences the first pipe.

That mismatch is the core reason end-to-end never felt trustworthy: **the architecture is a paragraph generator with a side diary**, not a **team** that divides labor under pressure.

### 0.2 Why it *looks* like “slop” (and what that really means)

Calling code “slop” is usually frustration talking. More precisely:

| Symptom you saw | What it usually means structurally |
|-----------------|-----------------------------------|
| Output jumps between [RESCUE], [STRENGTHEN], full paragraphs | One model is asked to **infer emotional state + pedagogy + mode** from **fragments** every time |
| Same conversation “forgets” the thread | History is **truncated** or merged poorly; there is no **durable deal memory** |
| UI stuck on “reasoning…” or empty | One stream carries **hidden reasoning + visible tags**; the UI must **guess** parse boundaries |
| Profiler insights feel irrelevant or late | Profiler runs on **clock time**, not **conversation milestones**; copilot does not **wait** or **merge** deterministically |
| “We added context injection / gates / buttons” but behavior barely improves | Those patches tune **symptoms** without changing the **single-writer bottleneck** |

None of that is fixed by “more careful prompting” alone, because the failure is **orchestration**, not wording.

### 0.3 The trap: every improvement fought the same ceiling

Past iterations often followed this loop:

1. **Observe failure** (mode thrash, truncation, drift).
2. **Add a patch** (debounce timing, bookend memory, rescue button, strip `<THINK>` harder).
3. **Ship** and discover a new failure mode because **the same LLM call still owns everything**.

That loop feels like shipping; it is actually **local optimization on a global bottleneck**. That is why teams report “we tried everything” while the product still **dumps text** that arrives **too late**, **too long**, or **wrong mode**.

### 0.4 Why we could not build MEDDPICC / SPIN / prep→live “end to end” on this spine

Sales frameworks are not labels on a paragraph. They are **state machines + evidence**:

- **MEDDPICC** needs persistent fields like “do we know economic buyer?” with **proof quotes** from the call — updated incrementally, not re-guessed each answer.
- **SPIN** needs **ordering discipline** (you don’t jump to Need-payoff without grounded Problem/Implication).
- **Prep → live** needs a **playbook object** that survives refresh, reconnect, and multi-device — not a JSON file baked in at build time.

The current system has **no first-class object** for “deal state” or “framework coverage.” It has **messages** to one chat brain. So every framework feature becomes **prompt fantasy**: the model *describes* MEDDPICC; it does not **own** MEDDPICC.

### 0.5 Why multi-agent is not “extra complexity” — it is how humans already run good calls

A great seller running a tough call is not one brain doing twelve jobs at once. They **partition**:

- **Ear** — track facts committed & risks.
- **Coach** — decide what matters *right now*.
- **Specialist** — pricing, security, clinical detail, demo script — only when triggered.

Multi-agent architecture mirrors that split so each piece can be:

- **Scoped** (small prompt, small failure domain),
- **Timed** (fast classifier vs slow writer),
- **Canceled** (live guidance preempts background analysis),
- **Verified** (structured JSON / schema instead of regex on prose).

### 0.6 What “done” looks like for the next team (so you stop looping)

End-to-end is not “SSE works.” It is:

1. **A persistent session object** (deal + playbook version + framework state).
2. **A supervisor** that chooses *one primary user-visible action* per beat (not three paragraphs).
3. **Specialists** invoked only when needed (objection handler, code/demo mode, framework updater).
4. **Structured outputs** to UI (cards), not tag soup — so rendering cannot collapse silently.
5. **Replay tests** that prove framework transitions on fixed transcripts.

Until those exist, MEDDPICC/SPIN will remain **theatre** and live alignment will keep **choking** under real speech pace.

